docs.abstract: The conventional wisdom is that a strong economy and stock markets help the incumbent party in midterm elections. Research doesn’t bear that out.
docs.snippet: The conventional wisdom is that a strong economy and stock markets help the incumbent party in midterm elections. Research doesn’t bear that out.
docs.lead_paragraph: Until markets plunged on Wednesday, the economic news couldn’t have been much better for Republicans heading into the midterm elections. Two weeks ago the Dow Jones industrial average hit a record. Last week the unemployment rate fell to 3.7 percent. Economic growth estimates were just upgraded to 4.2 percent for the second quarter.

headline.main: Markets Just Dived. Democrats Shouldn’t Get Too Excited.
headline.print_headline: Markets Tank, But Voters Don’t Mind

docs.abstract: Libor, a benchmark for everything from adjustable mortgages to private student loans, is set to disappear by 2021. Regulators are worried that banks aren’t taking the change seriously enough.
docs.snippet: Libor, a benchmark for everything from adjustable mortgages to private student loans, is set to disappear by 2021. Regulators are worried that banks aren’t taking the change seriously enough.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the world of finance, there is one number that arguably matters more than any other. You can find it in the small print on adjustable-rate mortgages and private student loans, it is the basis for enormous corporate loans, and it underpins nearly $200 trillion of derivatives contracts.

headline.main: The Most Important Number in Finance Is Going Away. Wall St. Isn’t Prepared.
headline.print_headline: A Key Bank Rate Is Expiring. Wall Street Isn’t Prepared.

docs.lead_paragraph: The bond market dominated the conversation on Wall Street this week as yields on benchmark Treasury bonds, which help determine interest rates for borrowers ranging from first-time home buyers to international corporations, steadily rose to seven-year highs.
